{
  "analysis": "From a human impact perspective, rewriting a service in Rust raises several practical concerns that need careful consideration. The primary question isn't whether Rust is technically superior, but whether the disruption and cost to the team and users is justified by real benefits they'll experience.\n\nThe human cost of a rewrite is significant. Your development team will spend weeks or months rebuilding something that already works, during which time they're not addressing user needs or fixing actual problems. There's learning curve overhead if team members aren't already proficient in Rust. There's also the risk of introducing new bugs during migration, potentially affecting service reliability that users depend on.\n\nHowever, if the current service has genuine problems affecting users - frequent outages, performance issues, security vulnerabilities, or maintenance burden that slows feature development - then a rewrite might be justified. Rust's memory safety could reduce crash-related downtime, and its performance characteristics might improve user experience.\n\nThe key question is whether users are actually suffering from problems that a Rust rewrite would solve, or whether this is primarily a technical preference. If the current service works reliably and meets user needs, the substantial investment in rewriting may not provide proportional value to the people who depend on the service.",
